I"c<p>The latest release of Google Chrome (30.0.1599.69.) snuck frequently visited sites back into your new tabs. I imagine this could be a semi-traumatic experience for some.</p>

<p><strong>Before</strong>
<img src="http://www.vincentbarr.com/assets/images/chrome-homepage-before.png" alt="Chrome Homepage Before" /></p>

<p><strong>After</strong>
<img src="http://www.vincentbarr.com/assets/images/chrome-homepage-after.png" alt="Chrome Homepage After" /></p>

<p>Take the following steps to drop your most frequently visited sites from new tabs.</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Open Chrome</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Enter ‘Chrome://flags’ in the address bar</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Press ⌘F and look for ‘Enable Instant Extended’</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p><img src="http://www.vincentbarr.com/assets/images/chrome-extended-api.png" alt="Extended API" /></p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Disable ‘Instant Extended API’</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Click ‘Ok’ when prompted to ‘Relaunch Now’</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>That’s better</p>
  </li>
</ol>

